ğŸ” WHAT IS PtH (Pass-the-Hash)?
PtH lets you authenticate with a hash instead of a plaintext password. Youâ€™re not cracking it. Youâ€™re using it as-is â€” because NTLM authentication accepts a valid hash as proof of identity.

âš ï¸ Hash = password for NTLM. If you got the hash, you got access.

ğŸ§  WHEN Can You Use PtH?
Once you:

ğŸ”“ Have admin rights on a box, and

ğŸª£ Extract NTLM hashes from:

SAM (local user hashes)

NTDS.dit (domain user hashes)

lsass.exe (active session hashes via tools like Mimikatz)

ğŸ’£ Why PtH Still Works in 2025
NTLM is still enabled for legacy compatibility.

Most orgs havenâ€™t fully disabled NTLM or configured mitigations like LAPS or Credential Guard.

